7:{"title":"Black Swan","director":"Darren Aronofsky","year":2010,"rating":9,"mood":"violet","story":"A ballet dancer's obsessive pursuit of perfection for the lead role in Swan Lake drives her to the edge of sanity.","why":"Creative obsession as self-destruction and self-discovery simultaneously — the terrifying intimacy between mastery and madness.","after":"You'll understand that some things can only be achieved by losing yourself in them.","direction":"Aronofsky uses horror conventions to get at something true about artistic intensity.","cinematography":"Matthew Libatique's handheld camera becomes Nina's unstable perspective.","musicSound":"Mansell's orchestral score and the Tchaikovsky it surrounds — the line between them dissolves.","impact":"Portman's performance is total commitment to the point of exhaustion. You believe her completely.","overall":"Divisive but undeniable — a film that takes artistic obsession at its word."}
8:{"title":"Whiplash","director":"Damien Chazelle","year":2014,"rating":9.2,"mood":"fire","story":"A young jazz drummer endures an abusive conductor's brutal teaching methods in his obsessive quest to become great.","why":"The question the film asks: is any level of self-destruction justified by the pursuit of excellence? It refuses to answer, which is the honest position.","after":"You'll have to decide for yourself whether greatness is worth what it costs.","direction":"Chazelle edits jazz into cinema — the rhythm of the cutting IS the rhythm of the music.","cinematography":"Close, sweaty, beautiful — the rehearsal room as a boxing ring and a temple simultaneously.","musicSound":"The music is the subject and the vehicle and the argument — all three.","impact":"The final performance sequence is one of the most thrillingly sustained sequences in modern film.","overall":"A film that refuses to moralize. Respects you enough to let you disagree with it."}
9:{"title":"All About Eve","director":"Joseph L. Mankiewicz","year":1950,"rating":9.3,"mood":"ash","story":"A seemingly devoted young fan insinuates herself into the life of a brilliant stage actress and begins replacing her with chilling, methodical precision.","why":"Creative obsession as theft — the consuming desire to be someone else, to have their gifts, their life, their place.","after":"You'll recognise the Eve in every room you've ever been in. Including yourself.","direction":"Mankiewicz's screenplay is a scalpel, and his direction knows exactly where to cut.","cinematography":"Milton Krasner photographs the theatre world as glamour built on anxious foundations.","musicSound":"Alfred Newman's score walks a fine line between the Broadway world it depicts and the darkness beneath.","impact":"Bette Davis's Margo is one of cinema's great characters — fully dimensional, magnificent, and terrified.","overall":"The wittiest, sharpest film about creative ambition and what it does to people. Essential."}
a:{"title":"Amadeus","director":"Miloš Forman","year":1984,"rating":9.4,"mood":"gold","story":"Court composer Salieri narrates his descent into obsessive jealousy of Mozart's genius — the burning humiliation of recognising greatness you cannot possess.","why":"The most devastating portrait of creative obsession: not the obsession with one's own work, but with someone else's talent.","after":"You'll feel the specific grief of loving something you can never fully reach.","direction":"Forman conducts a period epic with the psychological urgency of a thriller.","cinematography":"Miroslav Ondříček photographs 18th-century Vienna as a world of terrible, beautiful excess.","musicSound":"The music is not background — it is the argument, the subject, the catastrophe.","impact":"F. Murray Abraham's Salieri is one of cinema's great performances of contained, devastating envy.","overall":"One of the great studio films of its era — intelligent, operatic, unforgettable."}
b:{"title":"The Red Shoes","director":"Michael Powell & Emeric Pressburger","year":1948,"rating":9.2,"mood":"rose","story":"A ballet dancer is torn between love and the all-consuming demand of her art, embodied by an imperious impresario who will accept nothing less than total devotion.","why":"The original film about creative sacrifice — what it means to give art everything and what that costs you.","after":"You'll understand that the shoes don't ask for your soul. You give it before they can.","direction":"Powell and Pressburger work in a register that is pure dream-logic — film as enchantment.","cinematography":"Jack Cardiff's Technicolor is probably the most beautiful photography in cinema history.","musicSound":"Brian Easdale's ballet score within the film is a world inside a world.","impact":"The ballet sequence is 17 minutes of pure cinema — nothing like it has been made before or since.","overall":"One of the greatest films ever made. If you have never seen it, stop and watch it now."}
c:{"title":"Adaptation","director":"Charlie Kaufman & Spike Jonze","year":2002,"rating":8.8,"mood":"dusk","story":"A screenwriter tries to adapt an unadaptable book about orchid obsession and spirals into self-referential crisis — the film becoming his therapy and confession.","why":"The creative obsession that turns inward and devours itself. The paralysis of loving something so much you cannot touch it.","after":"You'll stop waiting for permission to make the imperfect thing.","direction":"Jonze and Kaufman make a film about making the film — and make it brilliant.","cinematography":"Lance Acord's lush Florida swamps versus Nicolas Cage's cramped, anxious interiors.","musicSound":"Carter Burwell's score is gentle, almost tender, for a film in full nervous collapse.","impact":"Nicolas Cage gives two of his best performances in one film. The double act is remarkable.","overall":"One of the cleverest, most genuinely human films about the act of creation."}
d:{"title":"Shine","director":"Scott Hicks","year":1996,"rating":8.6,"mood":"gold","story":"The true story of pianist David Helfgott, whose obsessive pursuit of musical greatness — encouraged and then crushed by a domineering father — leads to breakdown and eventual redemption.","why":"The cost of a gift pursued past the point the self can sustain — and the long road back from the break.","after":"You'll be grateful for every kindness that helped someone survive their obsession.","direction":"Hicks structures time non-linearly, making the film itself feel like a mind reconstructing itself.","cinematography":"Geoffrey Simpson photographs Australia and London with a dreamer's selective intensity.","musicSound":"The Rachmaninoff is not incidental. It is the film's emotional centre and the test that breaks the protagonist.","impact":"Geoffrey Rush's performance is a full surrender to another person's interior world.","overall":"A film that earns every tear it extracts. Unusually honest about the relationship between trauma and gift."}
e:{"title":"Florence Foster Jenkins","director":"Stephen Frears","year":2016,"rating":8.3,"mood":"rose","story":"The true story of a deluded socialite who was utterly convinced of her talent as a soprano — and who performed Carnegie Hall in 1944 to an audience that mostly could not believe what it was hearing.","why":"Obsession with a creative identity that has no basis in reality — the terrible beauty of someone who loves something more than they are good at it.","after":"You'll question whether delusion is always the enemy of art.","direction":"Frears handles the comedy and the tragedy in exact proportion — never mocking what he clearly loves.","cinematography":"Danny Cohen's period photography is warm, golden, and perfectly suited to a story about false light.","musicSound":"The juxtaposition of Jenkins's terrible singing with real operatic skill is the film's central joke and its central sadness.","impact":"Meryl Streep is devastating — you feel simultaneously like laughing and weeping.","overall":"About the purity of loving something, regardless of whether you are any good at it."}
f:{"title":"Ed Wood","director":"Tim Burton","year":1994,"rating":8.8,"mood":"ash","story":"The true story of Edward D. Wood Jr., considered the worst director in cinema history — and the most cheerfully, devastatingly obsessive filmmaker who ever lived.","why":"Creative obsession without talent — and the strange heroism of someone who pursues art with total conviction regardless of the result.","after":"You'll respect any creative act more. Even bad ones. Especially bad ones.","direction":"Burton shoots in black-and-white and finds in Wood's failure something genuinely moving.","cinematography":"Stefan Czapsky's shadows and angles give Wood's cheap world the look of expressionism.","musicSound":"Howard Shore's score plays with B-movie conventions while transcending them.","impact":"Johnny Depp's Ed Wood is one of his great early performances — pure enthusiasm as a tragic condition.","overall":"A love letter to the compulsive need to make things, regardless of consequence."}
10:{"title":"Mishima: A Life in Four Chapters","director":"Paul Schrader","year":1985,"rating":9,"mood":"fire","story":"A portrait of Japanese author Yukio Mishima, interweaving dramatizations of his novels with the events of his final day, when he died in a theatrical act of political obsession.","why":"Creative obsession fused with political obsession — the writer who built his art and his life around an idea and died for it.","after":"You'll think about what you would give everything for, and whether it would be worth it.","direction":"Schrader works in four visual registers simultaneously — an extraordinary structural achievement.","cinematography":"John Bailey and Eiko Ishioka create four distinct visual worlds within a single film.","musicSound":"Philip Glass's score is some of his finest work — rigorous and deeply felt.","impact":"One of the most formally ambitious American films of its decade. Absolutely singular.","overall":"A masterpiece that almost no one has seen. One of the great underseen films of the 1980s."}
12:["world","obsession","d"]
13:["emotion","creative-obsession","d"]
