on photographs Australia and London with a dreamer's selective intensity.","musicSound":"The Rachmaninoff is not incidental. It is the film's emotional centre and the test that breaks the protagonist.","impact":"Geoffrey Rush's performance is a full surrender to another person's interior world.","overall":"A film that earns every tear it extracts. Unusually honest about the relationship between trauma and gift."},{"title":"Florence Foster Jenkins","director":"Stephen Frears","year":2016,"rating":8.3,"mood":"rose","story":"The true story of a deluded socialite who was utterly convinced of her talent as a soprano — and who performed Carnegie Hall in 1944 to an audience that mostly could not believe what it was hearing.","why":"Obsession with a creative identity that has no basis in reality — the terrible beauty of someone who loves something more than they are good at it.","after":"You'll question whether delusion is always the enemy of art.","direction":"Frears handles the comedy and the tragedy in exact proportion — never mocking what he clearly loves.","cinematography":"Danny Cohen's period photography is warm, golden, and perfectly suited to a story about false light.","musicSound":"The juxtaposition of Jenkins's terrible singing with real operatic skill is the film's central joke and its central sadness.","impact":"Meryl Streep is devastating — you feel simultaneously like laughing and weeping.","overall":"About the purity of loving something, regardless of whether you are any good at it."},{"title":"Ed Wood","director":"Tim Burton","year":1994,"rating":8.8,"mood":"ash","story":"The true story of Edward D. Wood Jr., considered the worst director in cinema history — and the most cheerfully, devastatingly obsessive filmmaker who ever lived.","why":"Creative obsession without talent — and the strange heroism of someone who pursues art with total conviction regardless of the result.","after":"You'll respect any creative act more. Even bad ones. Especially bad ones.","direction":"Burton shoots in black-and-white and finds in Wood's failure something genuinely moving.","cinematography":"Stefan Czapsky's shadows and angles give Wood's cheap world the look of expressionism.","musicSound":"Howard Shore's score plays with B-movie conventions while transcending them.","impact":"Johnny Depp's Ed Wood is one of his great early performances — pure enthusiasm as a tragic condition.","overall":"A love letter to the compulsive need to make things, regardless of consequence."},{"title":"Mishima: A Life in Four Chapters","director":"Paul Schrader","year":1985,"rating":9,"mood":"fire","story":"A portrait of Japanese author Yukio Mishima, interweaving dramatizations of his novels with the events of his final day, when he died in a theatrical act of political obsession.","why":"Creative obsession fused with political obsession — the writer who built his art and his life around an idea and died for it.","after":"You'll think about what you would give everything for, and whether it would be worth it.","direction":"Schrader works in four visual registers simultaneously — an extraordinary structural achievement.","cinematography":"John Bailey and Eiko Ishioka create four distinct visual worlds within a single film.","musicSound":"Philip Glass's score is some of his finest work — rigorous and deeply felt.","impact":"One of the most formally ambitious American films of its decade. Absolutely singular.","overall":"A masterpiece that almost no one has seen. One of the great underseen films of the 1980s."}],"label":"10 films — quick browse"}]}],["$","div",null,{"className":"grid grid-cols-2 gap-x-3 gap-y-5 sm:grid-cols-2 md:grid-cols-3 lg:grid-cols-4 xl:grid-cols-4 sm:gap-x-5 sm:gap-y-7","children":[["$","$L6","Black Swan-2010",{"film":"$7"}],["$","$L6","Whiplash-2014",{"film":"$8"}],["$","$L6","All About Eve-1950",{"film":"$9"}],["$","$L6","Amadeus-1984",{"film":"$a"}],["$","$L6","The Red Shoes-1948",{"film":"$b"}],["$","$L6","Adaptation-2002",{"film":"